##a. Why did you select this data set?

It is small mammal data and I am in a mammalogy class, so I was interested.

##b. Who collected the data? Why?

Andrew Hope collected this data. The metadata doesnt explicitly say why, but from the title I am guessing they collected it to compare between species and between the 16 linear trapping transects in the 8 burn treatment watersheds in Konza Prarie. They could be comparing a number of things, but because they are looking at small mammal host-parasite sampling data I think they will be testing the presence and absence of specific parasites in different species and in different watersheds.

Data Citation: Hope, A. 2019. CSM08 Small mammal host-parasite sampling data for 16 linear trapping transects located in 8 LTER burn treatment watersheds at Konza Prairie ver 3. Environmental Data Initiative. https://doi.org/10.6073/pasta/69109c56fcf21a30a8d37369cb47f8de (Accessed 2022-11-30).

##c.What are the data measuring?

The data are measuring a lot of different things, including (but not limited to) the year of the sample, the date it was collected, the watershed (and therefore burn treatment), the transect within the watershed, the trap station within the transect, the species trapped (recorded as species code), the ear tag number, the specimen voucher number if it is going to a museum, the recapture status, the total length of the animal, the tail length of the animal, the hind foot length, the ear length, the weight, the sex, the age, and the reproductive condition.

  1. pull in data

  1. plot expected relationships

I think there will not be a significant difference in the number of species found in different watersheds.

Null hypothesis (Ho): The number of species found in each watershed is equal (no significant difference). Alternate hypothesis (Ha): The number of species found in each watershed is not equal (significant difference).

###c.What statistical test did you employ to test your hypothesis? Why did you select that test?

explanatory = Watershed = categorical nominal response = length.unique.Species.. = discrete quantitative

This will be a chi squared test because Watershed (the expanatory or predictor variable) is a categorical nominal variable and length.unique.Species.. (the response variable) is a quantitative discrete variable. (Based on the chart we were provided with.)

###d.What was the outcome of your test?

5.a) make a matrix

5.b) make the model

A1.chi<-chisq.test(A1.mat)

## [7] "expected"  "residuals" "stdres"

A1.chi
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  A1.mat
## X-squared = 1.8727, df = 7, p-value = 0.9665

Null hypothesis (Ho): The number of species found in each watershed is equal. Alternate hypothesis (Ha): The number of species found in each watershed is not equal.

p-value=0.9665 0.9665>0.05 fail to reject the null

There is not a significant difference in the number of species found in each watershed based on a p-value of 0.9665.

  ylab("Avgerage Weight")

I think there will not be a significant difference in the average weight of animals (SIHI and MIOC) found in different watersheds.

Null hypothesis (Ho): The average weight of these species found in each watershed is equal (no significant difference). Alternate hypothesis (Ha): The average weight of these species found in each watershed is not equal (significant difference).

###c.What statistical test did you employ to test your hypothesis? Why did you select that test?

As this data is currently, this is a one-way anova. This is the correct test because the response variable (or y) is average weight which is a quantitative continuous variable, and the predictor/explanatory (or x) is Watershed which is categorical. I am asking about difference in group means, which makes this an anova. If I wanted this to be a two-way anova, I would have to add another categorical variable (column) to the dataframe that could also impact weight, and could be influenced by or influence watershed.

###c.What statistical test did you employ to test your hypothesis? Why did you select that test?

This test is an anova using glm. This is the correct test because the response variable (or y) is the Shannon diversity index which is a quantitative continuous variable, and the predictor/explanatory (or x) is Watershed which is categorical. I am using glm() because this data doesnt fit the linear model (lm()) distribution requirements.
